remarks.format:
## Remarks
`SKFourByteTag` represents an OpenType four-byte tag — a sequence of four ASCII characters packed into a 32-bit unsigned integer. Tags are used throughout OpenType to identify tables, variation axes, and features. For example, `'wght'` identifies the weight axis and `'cmap'` identifies the character map table.
Characters are packed in big-endian order: the first character occupies bits 31–24 (the most-significant byte). Use <see cref="M:SkiaSharp.SKFourByteTag.Parse(System.String)" /> for a convenient string-based construction; strings shorter than four characters are right-padded with spaces.
This is a value type; no disposal is required.
## Examples
```csharp // Construct from four characters var wght = new SKFourByteTag('w', 'e', 'i', 'g'); // not standard — use Parse var wght2 = SKFourByteTag.Parse("wght");
// Implicit conversion to/from uint uint raw = wght2; SKFourByteTag fromUint = (SKFourByteTag)0x77676874u; // implicit
// Round-trip through string Console.WriteLine(wght2.ToString()); // "wght" ```
